Wi-Fi security is very important in IoT because devices such as ESP32 send and receive data over wireless networks. If the network is not secure, attackers can steal data or gain unauthorized access. Two common Wi-Fi attack vectors are WPA2 vulnerabilities and Evil Twin attacks. Some older WPA2 implementations are vulnerable to security weaknesses if devices are not updated. In an Evil Twin attack, an attacker creates a fake Wi-Fi network with the same name (SSID) as the real one. IoT devices may connect to the fake network, allowing the attacker to intercept or modify data.
To improve ESP32 Wi-Fi security, developers should use WPA3 whenever it is available because it provides stronger authentication and better protection than WPA2. Another good practice is certificate pinning, where the ESP32 verifies the server’s trusted certificate before sending data. This helps prevent man-in-the-middle attacks. Developers should also use HTTPS/TLS encryption, keep firmware updated, and use strong, unique Wi-Fi passwords. Disabling unused services and enabling secure boot and flash encryption (when supported) further improves security.
Hardcoding Wi-Fi passwords or API keys directly in the source code is dangerous. If the code is uploaded to GitHub or shared with others, the credentials can be exposed. Attackers may then access the Wi-Fi network or cloud services. A better approach is to store sensitive information in a separate configuration file (such as config.h), exclude it from GitHub using .gitignore, or use secure storage mechanisms.
By following these security practices, ESP32-based IoT devices become more secure, reliable, and resistant to common wireless attacks.
